rcraft carrier to be commissioned in the world.\nBULLET::::- 1927 – Kern and Hammerstein's musical play \"Show Boat\", considered to be the first true American musical play, opens at the Ziegfeld Theatre on Broadway.\nBULLET::::- 1929 – Soviet General Secretary Joseph Stalin orders the \"liquidation of the kulaks as a class\".\nBULLET::::- 1932 – Radio City Music Hall, \"Showplace of the Nation\", opens in New York City.\nBULLET::::- 1935 – Regina Jonas is ordained as the first female rabbi in the history of Judaism.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – The 7.8 Erzincan earthquake shakes eastern Turkey with a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (\"Extreme\"). At least 32,700 people were killed.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – Winter War: Finland holds off a Soviet attack in the Battle of Kelja.\nBULLET::::- 1945 – The International Monetary Fund is created with the signing of an agreement by 29 nations.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – Indonesian National Revolution: The Netherlands officially recognizes Indonesian independence. End of the Dutch East Indies.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – The Cave of Swallows, the largest known cave shaft in the world, is discovered in Aquismón, San Luis Potosí, Mexico.\nBULLET::::- 1968 – Apollo program: \"Apollo 8\" splashes down in the Pacific Ocean, ending the first orbital manned mission to the Moon.\nBULLET::::- 1978 – Spain becomes a democracy after 40 years of fascist dictatorship.\nBULLET::::- 1979 – The Soviet Union invades the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan.\nBULLET::::- 1983 – Pope John Paul II visits Mehmet Ali Ağca in Rebibbia's prison and personally forgives him for the 1981 attack on him in St. Peter's Square.\nBULLET::::- 1985 – Palestinian guerrillas kill eighteen people inside the airports of Rome, Italy, and Vienna, Austria.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – The Romanian Revolution concludes, as the last minor street confrontations and stray shootings abruptly end in the country's capital, Bucharest.\nBULLET::::- 1996 – Taliban forces retake the strategic Bagram Airfield which solidifies their buffer zone around Kabul, Afghanistan.\nBULLET::::- 1997 – Protestant paramilitary leader Billy Wright is assassinated in Northern Ireland, United Kingdom.\nBULLET::::- 2002 – Two truck bombs kill 72 and wound 200 at the pro-Moscow headquarters of the Chechen government in Grozny, Chechnya, Russia.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – Radiation from an explosion on the magnetar SGR 1806-20 reaches Earth. It is the brightest extrasolar event known to have been witnessed on the planet.\nBULLET::::- 2007 – Former Pakistani prime minister Benazir Bhutto is assassinated in a shooting incident.\nBULLET::::- 2007 – Riots erupt in Mombasa, Kenya, after Mwai Kibaki is declared the winner of the presidential election, triggering a political, economic, and humanitarian crisis.\nBULLET::::- 2008 – Operation Cast Lead: Israel launches 3-week operation on Gaza.\nBULLET::::- 2009 – Iranian election protests: On the Day of Ashura in Tehran, Iran, government security forces fire upon demonstrators.\n\nBULLET::::- 1350 – John I of Aragon (d. 1395)\nBULLET::::- 1390 – Anne de Mortimer, claimant to the English throne (d. 1411)\nBULLET::::- 1459 – John I Albert (d. 1501)\nBULLET::::- 1481 – Casimir, Margrave of Brandenburg-Bayreuth, Margrave of Bayreuth (d. 1527)\nBULLET::::- 1493 – Johann Pfeffinger, German theologian (d. 1573)\nBULLET::::- 1566 – Jan Jesenius, Bohemian physician, politician and philosopher (d. 1621)\nBULLET::::- 1571 – Johannes Kepler, German mathematician, astronomer, and astrologer (d. 1630)\nBULLET::::- 1572 – Johannes Vodnianus Campanus, Czech poet, playwright, and composer (d. 1622)\nBULLET::::- 1584 – Philipp Julius, Duke of Pomerania (d. 1625)\nBULLET::::- 1595 – Bohdan Khmelnytsky, hetman of Ukraine (d. 1657)\nBULLET::::- 1683 – Conyers Middleton, English priest and theologian (d. 1750)\nBULLET::::- 1714 – George Whitefield, English preacher and saint (d. 1770)\nBULLET::::- 1715 – Philippe de Noailles, French general (d. 1794)\nBULLET::::- 1721 – François Hems